8621000 16735000 4100000 4100000 2800000 0 0 109100000 114903000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">14. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We and certain current and former officers and directors have been named as defendants in complaints filed by investors in the United States District Court for the District of Colorado. The first complaint was filed in November 2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September 2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December 2008. The amended complaint purports to state claims under Section 10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April 2, 2007 and April 14, 2008 (the &#x201C;Class Period&#x201D;). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleges that, during the Class Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common stock was artificially inflated. The amended complaint also claims that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint seeks compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also added attorneys&#x2019; fees and costs of litigation. On February 28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit.&nbsp;&nbsp;We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants have entered into a Stipulation of Settlement with the plaintiffs that would, if approved by the United States District Court for the District of Colorado, resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class, and plaintiffs&#x2019; appeal would be dismissed. Our independent auditor is not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement is subject to customary conditions, including preliminary court approval, and final court approval following notice to stockholders. If the settlement becomes final, all amounts required by the settlement will be paid by our insurers. There can be no assurance that the settlement will be finally approved by the District Court, or that approval by the District Court will, if challenged, be upheld by the Tenth Circuit.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On October 27, 2010, Spectrum Agencies (&#x201C;Spectrum&#x201D;) filed suit against our subsidiary, Crocs Europe B.V. (&#x201C;Crocs Europe&#x201D;), in the High Court of Justice, Queen&#x2019;s Bench Division, Royal Courts of Justice in London, United Kingdom (&#x201C;UK&#x201D;). Spectrum acted as an agent for Crocs products in the UK from 2005 until Crocs Europe terminated the relationship on July 3, 2008 due to Spectrum&#x2019;s breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe. Spectrum alleges that Crocs Europe unlawfully terminated the agency relationship and failed to pay certain sales commissions. A trial on the liability, not quantum (compensation and damages), was held at the High Court in London from November 30, 2011 to December 5, 2011. On December 16, 2011, the High Court of Justice issued a judgment that found that although Spectrum&#x2019;s actions were a breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe the breach was not sufficiently severe to justify termination. We believe that the trial judge erred in his findings and subsequently appealed the judgment.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 30, 2012, the Court of Appeal handed down its judgment confirming the trial judge&#x2019;s findings. We submitted a request to the Supreme Court seeking permission to appeal.&nbsp;&nbsp;On April 24, 2013 the Supreme Court declined to grant permission to appeal.&nbsp;&nbsp;Given that this phase of the proceedings only pertains to liability, there have been no findings in relation to the amount of compensation or damages other than with respect to legal fees. Under English law, the prevailing party is entitled to reimbursement of reasonable legal fees incurred in the proceedings. We expect that Spectrum will now request to move to the damages phase via a case management conference, during which the Court will provide instructions and schedules leading up to the trial on damages.&nbsp;&nbsp;Spectrum has not quantified its claim for compensation and damages and the amount will be assessed later in the proceedings.&nbsp;&nbsp;A judgment on damages could take up to 12 months.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We are currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs &amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of the period from 2006 to 2010. CBP issued a draft audit report to which we filed comments and objections.&nbsp; We believe that a final report (and notice of a formal claim) will not be issued until sometime in mid-2013.&nbsp; CBP has provided us with preliminary projections and a draft audit report that reflect unpaid duties totaling approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">14.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million during the period under review. We have responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is considerably less than the preliminary projection.&nbsp; CBP is currently reviewing this response.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict whether our arguments will be successful in eliminating or reducing the amount in dispute. Likewise, it is not possible to predict whether CBP may seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any loss of revenue claim.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) audited the period from January 2006 to July 2011.&nbsp; There were two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods and the second for raw materials.&nbsp; The first phase was completed and no major discrepancies were noted by the SAT.&nbsp; On January 9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT issued a tax assessment (taxes and penalties</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">) of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">280.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">22.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million) bas</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw materials during the audit period.&nbsp; We believe that the proposed penalty amount is unfounded and without merit. With the help of local counsel we filed an appeal by the deadline of March 15, 2013.&nbsp; We have argued that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially les</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s than that proposed by the SAT.&nbsp; In connection with the appeal, the SAT required us to post an appeal surety bond in the amount of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">321.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">26.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million), which amo</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">unt reflects estimated additional penalties and interest if we are not successful on our appeal.&nbsp; This amount will be adjusted on an annual basis. We expect it to take between two and three years for resolution of this matter in the Mexican courts.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter or reasonably estimate any potential loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As of March 31, 2013, we have accrued a total </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">5.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million relat</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed to these legal matters.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Although we are subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, we are not party to any other pending legal proceedings that we believe will have a material adverse impact on our business.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"></font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 119000 768000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <div <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Purchase Commitments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">A</font><font style="display: inline;">s of </font><font style="display: inline;">March 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had purchase commitments with certain third party manufacturers f</font><font style="display: inline;">or $</font><font style="display: inline;">143.1</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, of which $</font><font style="display: inline;">6.1</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million was for yet-to-be-received finished product where title passes to us upon receipt</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">As of December 31, 2012, we had purchase commitments with certain third party manufacturers for $</font><font style="display: inline;">152.8</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, of which $</font><font style="display: inline;">5.9</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million was</font><font style="display: inline;"> for ye</font><font style="display: inline;">t-to-be-received finished product where title passes to us upon receipt</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Government </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Tax Audit Contingencies</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We are regularly </font><font style="display: inline;">subject to, and are currently undergoing, audits by tax authorities in the United States and foreign jurisdictions for prior tax years. In April 2013, the Brazilian government claimed we improperly reduced sales tax owed to the government&nbsp;by $</font><font style="display: inline;">2.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million related to our use o</font><font style="display: inline;">f go</font><font style="display: inline;">vernment obligations purchased by us and applied as payments against the sales tax ("tax credits")&nbsp;for the period April 2009 to May 2011, bringing the cumulative assessed tax to approximately&nbsp;$</font><font style="display: inline;">4.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million.&nbsp;Penalties and interest have also been assessed at approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">9.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">We believe our tax estimates are reasonable and sales tax returns, along with the utilization of the tax credits, have been p</font><font style="display: inline;">roperly filed and reported in our</font><font style="display: inline;"> financial statements. We intend to defend our positions </font><font style="display: inline;">through litigation if necessary; </font><font style="display: inline;">however,&nbsp;the final outcome of tax audits and related litigation, including the assessment of potentially significant penalties and interest, is inherently uncertain and could be materially different than that reflected in our historical income tax provisions and accruals.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 0.001 0.001 250000000 250000000 91047297 91327712 88662845 88102196 91000 92000 34766000 24943000 8766000 10180000 126999000 145807000 800000 1600000 1600000 800000 6635000 9362000 6600000 3100000 0.0263 0.0245 2012-12-10 2013-03-25 2016-09-01 2016-09-01 400000 200000 6284000 5868000 34112000 33722000 2405000 2440000 5500000 6100000 8353000 2234000 1308000 606000 417000 4565000 1543000 2245000 10264000 2542000 1278000 1150000 401000 5371000 2117000 2776000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">7. DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We have entered into foreign currency exchange forward contract and currency swap derivative instruments to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. We do not designate these derivative instruments as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging. Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recognized in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2018;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2019;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> in our </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">consolidated statements of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">income</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. For purposes of the </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">condensed consolidated statement of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">cash flow</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, the Company classifies the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2018;Cash provided by (used in) operating a</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ctivities.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2019; See Note 6 &#x2013; &#x201C;Fair Value Measurements&#x201D; for further details regarding the fair values of the corresponding derivative assets and liabilities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts at </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">March 31, 2013 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">December 31, 2012. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U.S. dollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of our exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">9. STOCK-BASED COMPENSATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:6pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Options granted generally vest on a straight-line basis over four years with the first year vesting on a cliff basis followed by monthly vesting for the remaining three years. Restricted stock awards (&#x201C;RSA&#x201D;) and restricted stock units (&#x201C;RSU&#x201D;) granted generally vest on a straight-line basis over three or four years depending on the terms of the grant. Stock-based compensation expense is recognized on a straight-line basis over the applicable vesting period and is recognized in the &#x2018;Cost of sales&#x2019; and &#x2018;Selling, general and administrative&#x2019; expense line items in the condensed consolidated statements of income. During the three months ended March 31, 2013 and 2012, </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">3.5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million and New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restricted Stock Awards and Units</font> </p> <p style="margin:6pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">From time to time, we grant RSAs and RSUs to our employees. Unvested RSAs have the same rights as those of common shares including voting rights and non-forfeitable dividend rights. However, ownership of unvested RSAs cannot be transferred until they are vested. An unvested RSU is a contractual right to receive a share of common stock only upon its vesting. RSUs have dividend equivalent rights which accrue over the term of the award and are paid if and when the RSUs vest, but they have no voting rights.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three months ended March 31, 2013 and 2012, the Board of Directors approved RSU grants </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, respectively, of which </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.6</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, respectively, were granted to certain executives as part of a performance incentive program. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Half of these performance incentive program grants vest ratably on each of the first three anniversaries of the grant date; 25% will vest upon achievement of certain performance metrics; and the remaining 25% will vest one year from the date upon which certain performance metrics are achieved. If actual performance metrics exceed the targeted performance metrics by a predetermined amount, the executives are eligible to receive up to 200% of the performance-based portion of their award.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> During the three months ended March 31, 2013 </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">and 2012, $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.1</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and an </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">immateri</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">al</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> amount, respectively, of stock-based payment expense related to these RSUs were recorded.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table summarizes the RSA activity for the three months ended March 31, 2013 and 2012:</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of our non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impai</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">rment charge would be recorded.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 49169000 4856000 3522000 33933000 6222000 636000 53371000 4765000 3699000 37766000 6189000 952000 5254000 14298000 6171000 8995000 10469000 13586000 106258000 4856000 6161000 87426000 7145000 670000 112144000 4765000 6177000 93278000 6966000 958000 57089000 2639000 53493000 923000 34000 58773000 2478000 55512000 777000 6000 5548000 5548000 14107000 14107000 295000 295000 214000 214000 -4276000 -2600000 -8147000 -2982000 20827000 21786000 -2104000 -9941000 2729000 2645000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4. <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1. GENERAL</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Organization</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;"> - </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. and its subsidiaries (collectively the &#x201C;Company,&#x201D; &#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;our&#x201D; or &#x201C;us&#x201D;) are engaged in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing and distribution of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Basis of Presentation &amp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;"> - </font><font style="display: inline;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. Accordingly, these statements do not include all of the information and disclosures required by GAAP or SEC rules&nbsp;and regulations for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair presentation of the results for the interim periods presented. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">These statements should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and footnotes included in the Company&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December 31, 2012 (the &#x201C;2012 Form&nbsp;10-K&#x201D;). The accounting policies used in preparing these unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements are the same as those described in Note&nbsp;1 &#x2013; &#x201C;Organization and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies&#x201D; to the consolidated financial statements in the 2012 Form&nbsp;10-K.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Use of Estimates</font><font style="display: inline;"> - The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates, judgments and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Management believes that the estimates, judgments and assumptions made when accounting for items and matters such as, but not limited to, the allowance for doubtful accounts, sales returns and discounts, impairment assessments and charges, recoverability of assets (including deferred tax assets), uncertain tax positions, share-based compensation expense, useful lives assigned to long-lived assets, depreciation and provisions for contingencies are reasonable based on information available at the time they are made. Management also makes estimates in the assessments of potential losses in relation to threatened or pending legal and tax matters (see Note 14 &#x2013; &#x201C;Legal Proceedings&#x201D;). Actual results could materially differ from these estimates. For matters not related to income taxes, if a loss is considered probable and the amount can be reasonably estimated, the Company recognizes an expense for the estimated loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Noncontrolling Interests</font><font style="display: inline;"> - As of March 31, 2013, all of our subsidiaries were, in substance, wholly owned.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Accumulated Other Comprehensive Income</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2013; Activity within our accumulated other comprehensive income (&#x201C;AOCI&#x201D;) balance consists solely of gains and losses resulting from the translation of foreign subsidiary financial statements to our reporting currency.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Foreign currency translation resulting in changes to other comprehensive income and related reclassification adjustments are presented gross rather net of tax on the condensed consolidated statements of other comprehensive income.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Adopted Accounting Standards</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In December 2011, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued Accounting Standards Update (ASU) No.&nbsp;2011-11 </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Balance Sheet (Topic 210) Disclosures about Offsetting Assets and Liabilities</font><font style="display: inline;"> (&#x201C;ASU No.&nbsp;2011-11&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This pronouncement was issued to enhance disclosure requirements surrounding the nature of an entity&#x2019;s right to offset and related arrangements associated with its financial instruments and derivative instruments. This new guidance requires companies to disclose both gross and net information about instruments and transactions eligible for offset in the statement of financial position and instruments and transactions subject to master netting arrangements. This pronouncement was effective for us on January 1, 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;As the provisions of ASU No. 2011-11 relate only to financial statement disclosures regarding balance sheet offsetting, the adoption of ASU No. 2011-11 did not have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements. ASU No.&nbsp;2011-11 was subsequently amended by ASU No.&nbsp;2013-01.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In January 20</font><font style="display: inline;">13, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2013-01 </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Balance Sheet (Topic 210): Clarifying the Scope of Disclosures about Offsetting Assets and Liabilities</font><font style="display: inline;"> (&#x201C;ASU No.&nbsp;2013-01&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;This pronouncement was issued to address implementation issues about the scope of Accounting Standards Update No. 2011-11 and to clarify the scope of the offsetting disclosures and address any unintended consequences. This pronouncement is effective for us on January 1, 2013. The provisions of ASU No. 2013-01 relate only to the clarification of ASU 2011-11 and, accordingly, its adoption did not have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In February 2013, the FASB issued </font><font style="display: inline;">ASU No.&nbsp;2013-02 </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Comprehensive Income (Topic 220): Reporting of Amounts Reclassified Out of Accumulated Other Comprehensive Income</font><font style="display: inline;"> (&#x201C;ASU No.&nbsp;2013-02&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This pronouncement requires an entity to report the effect of significant reclassifications out of accumulated other comprehensive income for each applicable component of net income on a prospective basis.&nbsp; This pronouncement is effective for us on January 1, 2013. The provisions of ASU No.&nbsp;2013-02 relate only to financial statement presentation of other comprehensive income and, accordingly, its adoption did not have an impact on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial position or the results of its operations.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Issued Accounting Standards</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In March 2013, the FASB issued ASU No. 2013-05 </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Foreign Currency Matters (Topic 830): Parent&#x2019;s Accounting for the Cumulative Translation Adjustment upon Derecognition of Certain Subsidiaries</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;"> or Groups of Assets within a Foreign Entity or of an Investment in a Foreign Entity</font><font style="display: inline;"> (&#x201C;ASU No.&nbsp;2013-05&#x201D;). This pronouncement provides clarification around the release of any cumulative translation adjustment related to when the parent ceases to have controlling financial interest in a business or group of assets held within a foreign entity. This pronouncement is effective prospectively for reporting periods beginning on or after December 15, 2013, and interim periods within those annual periods. We do not anticipate the adoption of ASU 2013-05 to have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 8835000 9776000 713000 40239000 49135000 -7078000 4317000 13361000 13546000 -1001000 -419000 598000 334000 172000 115000 12661000 1838000 5745000 7836000 9889000 0.001 0.001 5000000 5000000 0 0 24967000 27047000 656000 603000 51000000 12173000 319000 515000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">3. 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">13. OPERATING SEGMENTS &amp; GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the first quarter of 2013</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">we adjusted our operating segment structure for internal reports reviewed by the chief operating decision maker (&#x201C;CODM&#x201D;) by carving-out Japan from the Asia Pacific segment and adding Japan as a separate operating segment. This change was made due to recurring amounts of substantial business activity as well as the macroeconomic environment within Japan, which resulted in the need for a regular review of Japan operating results by management and the CODM in order to better evaluate performance and allocate resources for the consolidated business. Segment information for all periods presented has been reclassified to conform to fiscal 2013 presentation.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As a result of the changes discussed above, w</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e have four reportable operating segments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> based on the geographic nature of our operations</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">: Americas,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Asia Pacific, Japan and Europe. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We also have an &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category which aggregates insignificant operating segments that do not meet the reportable threshold and represent manufacturing o</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">perations located in Mexico, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Italy</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and Asia. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The composition of our reportable operating segments is consistent with that used by our </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">CODM</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to evaluate performance and allocate resources.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Each of our reportable operating segments derives its revenues from the sale of footwear, apparel and accessories to external customers</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as well as intersegment sales</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. Revenues of the &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category are primaril</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">y made up of intersegment sales</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The remaining revenues for the &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; represent non-footwear produ</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ct sales to external customers. Intersegment sales are not included in the measurement of segment operating income or regularly reviewed by the CODM and are eliminated when deriving total consolidated revenues.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The primary </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">financial </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">measure utilized by the CODM to evaluate performance and allocate resources is segment operating income. Segment performance evaluation is based primarily on segment results without allocating corporate expenses, or indirect general, ad</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ministrative and other expenses. Segment profits or losses of our reportable operating segments include adjustments to eliminate intersegment profit or losses on intersegment sales. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As such, reconciling items for segment operating income represent unallocated corporate and other expenses as well as intersegment eliminations. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Segment assets consist of cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable and inventory</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as these balances are regularly reviewed by the CODM</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 12pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table sets forth information related to our reportable operating business segments during the three months ended March 31, 2013 and 2012:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0"
